## WHAT YOU'RE LOOKING AT

That one section carries: purpose, what's assessed, why it matters, review criteria with framework references, six red flags, a good-practice definition, an evidence tier bar, sampling guidance, four document requirements each with their own review checklist and common-deficiency list, ten inputs with assessor guidance, risk weights, auto-finding triggers, and a grid. It's a real workpaper.

TRM has five domains. At roughly 3–5 sections per domain, that's ~20 sections × this depth. Then four more frameworks.

**Two things before I keep going:**

1. **Look at TRM.TG.01 and tell me where I'm wrong.** You're a CTP — the treasury content is the part you'll see through instantly. Is the review criteria right? Are the red flags the real ones? Is "board approval" the right bar, or do your clients' structures make that unrealistic?

2. **The content problem is now unavoidable.** I can build all 20 TRM sections at this depth from treasury practice. But GRC-A, REG-C, ICAEF, and TrustFabric are *your* frameworks — their objectives and exam points aren't inferable from an infographic with garbled text. If I draft them, you're auditing clients against controls I invented. Paste even rough bullets per domain and they become real.

